dataset.title: City of Seattle, Cedar River Watershed, Forest Mapping and Inventory of Priority Ecological Thinning Areas 2001 - 2020

creator.organizationName: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities

abstract.para: The Cedar River Watershed Habitat Conservation Plan commits to upland forest restoration work that will accelerate the development of old-forest conditions, improve habitat complexity, and increase biological diversity. The ecological thinning program strives to achieve these objectives. Strategic Planning for integrated HCP restoration activities has identified three priority areas for ecological thinning. This inventory project will sample 2,720 acres in three high priority areas, collect forest habitat data and provide information to forest restoration planning efforts. This field-based information will augment remote sensing image data and outdated field information, and will be used to design restoration projects.

description.para: The consultant shall prepare a digital representation of all forest polygons within the delineated priority areas that total 2,720 acres. Minimum size for forest polygons shall be 10 acres.

The plot level information collected in this inventory will be used to calculate the following forest characteristics to be used in planning upland and riparian forest restoration projects in the Cedar River Municipal Watershed:
- Size and distribution of standing dead wood
- Down wood volume and size distribution

Sampling plots for the three delineated areas (approximately 2,720 acres) will be systematically distributed over each inventory unit on a square grid with a density of one plot per four acres or no less than 8 plots per inventory unit. Proportional radius plots, fixed-area plots (1/100 acre), or a nested plot design may be used depending on tree size distribution. Proportional radius plots should be used for trees >8.9” DBH, fixed radius plots should be used for trees ≤ 8.9” DBH. Both PR plots and nested plots may be required in one location depending on diameter distribution within plots.

Information to be collected on all sample trees includes species, DBH, crown ratio, and log grades of all trees > 5 inch DBH. On trees with DBH < 5 inches, DBH will be measured to the nearest 1 inch. Trees falling into the same diameter class can be tallied by species. On trees with DBH ³ 5 inches, DBH will be measured to the nearest 1/10th inch. Live crown ratio will be estimated or measured to the nearest 10% on all sample trees.

Snags: On all standing dead trees > 5 inch DBH, DBH will be measured to the nearest 2 inch, and height and decay class will be estimated. Refer to Appendix E, Down Wood (CWD) and Snag Decay Class Descriptions.

Tree height and crown measurements: Tree heights and crown lengths will be measured on a sub-sample proportional to diameter distribution, but no less than 30% of sample trees per inventory unit. Tree height measurements should be evenly distributed over the inventory unit. To calculate site index for two dominant species, total height and age at breast height, determined from increment cores, will be measured on six dominant/co-dominant trees per inventory unit. Minimum sample size per inventory unit is six trees per selected species Five-year height growth increment of understory trees (< 5 inch DBH) will be determined for six trees per species and inventory unit to the nearest 1/10th foot. Minimum tree height for height growth measurements is 6” total height.

Radial growth: Radial growth increment (10 years, measured to the nearest 1/20th inch) will be determined on one tree per sample plot for trees > 5 inch DBH of 2-3 dominant species, sampled proportional to squared-DBH.
Tree damage: Tree damage will be recorded on all trees. Refer to Appendix D, Insect, Disease and Damage Codes.

Understory Vegetation: Data on understory vegetation will be sampled on 1/100 acre fixed-area plots at the same location as the tree stratum plot. Understory trees species (> 6 inch and < 4.5 feet tall) will be counted by species. Cover percent by shrub species and herbaceous indicator species will be determined by ocular estimate in 10% cover classes. Refer to Appendix F, List of Indicator Species.

Information on down wood will be collected using line-intercept sampling (LIS) or point relascope sampling (PRS). LIS will be conducted on one transect (100’ long) per 20 acres, with a minimum of 3 transects per inventory unit. Data collected on down wood will include log midpoint diameter and decay class. Refer to Appendix E, Down Wood (CWD) and Snag Decay Class Descriptions. Minimum log diameter at intercept is 5 inches. Transects will be evenly distributed throughout the unit, starting at an inventory plot location, laid out in a randomly chosen compass direction. Location (plot number) and azimuth of the LIS transect shall be recorded with the down wood data. PRS sampling will be conducted at each inventory point following procedures by Gove et al. 2001 (Journal of Forestry, Vol. 99(4): 4-11), using a 2:1 (reach: width) relascope. Mid-point diameter or diameter at large and small end, and decay class will be recorded for each log counted.

Georeferencing: The location of each plot center should be recorded using GPS. In case of limited signal reception (canopy cover) or satellite availability, a minimum of 25% of plots within each inventory unit will be recorded. The GPS coordinates are to include the plot identifier in agreement with that used in the field data.

Digital Photos: A minimum of 3 digital photos shall be taken for each sampled polygon. Photos should be taken to best represent the polygon including down wood and understory vegetation using scaled referencing. SPU realizes that photo conditions are extremely variable and many photos will likely be taken with inadequate light resulting in poor quality images.
Forest Insect, Disease and Damage Assessment

Observations on biotic (including forest insects and pathogens) and abiotic tree damage outside of plots will be mapped and recorded as field notes. Minimum level of coding should include the required codes 01-99. Refer to SPU classification in Appendix D.

Riparian forest conditions will be assessed during the forest inventory. Where riparian forests are delineated during digital mapping, inventory information will be collected according to above protocol. Riparian areas of small extent (along streams on steep slopes, incorporated riparian areas) are treated as part of the upland forest inventory unit. Notable changes in structure and composition associated with incorporated riparian areas or other unique habitat features will be noted in the comments. Such features may include: rock outcrops, seeps, waterfalls, aggregations of large logs or stumps, slash piles, patches of deciduous trees or shrubs, and unique species such as Western white pine or western yew.

When non-forest polygons are observed in the field, crew personnel shall make note of these polygons by assigning the appropriate special habitat classification using SPU’s Special Habitat Classification – Appendix B. This information will be used by the Consultant for augmenting and correcting assigned Special Habitat Classifications for non-forest polygons. Digital photos shall be taken of these locations.

Crew personnel shall make note of major wildlife species encountered (e.g., black-tailed deer, black bear, etc.), especially atypical/unusual wildlife sightings (e.g., bald or golden eagle, mountain goat, cougar, bobcat, etc.), atypical/unusual habitat features (e. g., caves, cliffs, talus, seeps, wetlands, etc.), atypical/unusual types (e.g., cougar tracks, dens, nest trees, skeletons, salt licks, beaver dams, bear damage, etc.) or amounts (e.g., heavily browsed areas, extensive bear damage, deer rubbing use, etc.) of wildlife sign using SPU’s Notable Wildlife Species/Attributes - Appendix G. Digital photos and GPS coordinates of atypical/unusual habitat features and types shall be recorded whenever possible, otherwise locations should be flagged and referenced to the nearest plot location.

Crew personnel shall make note of any observed historic or pre-historic cultural resources (50 years or older) using SPU’s Notable Cultural Resource Attributes – Appendix H. Examples include past homestead debris such as buildings, foundations, garbage sites, logging camp debris, railroad debris, culturally modified trees. Flagging shall be used for future investigation of these sites. Digital photos and GPS coordinates shall be recorded at these locations where possible.

The Consultant shall provide a check cruiser to oversee the quality of data that is collected. This person shall be responsible for ensuring that the plots are accurately located on the ground and that the data being collected is accurate and consistent among field crew personnel. A minimum of 68 or 10% of the total plots is required. The Consultant and SPU shall agree upon a sampling protocol for these quality control plots.

project.abstract: Augmentation of forest inventory [N54503] If needed, the City will design and conduct an appropriate sampling program to augment existing forest and habitat inventory data for the watershed. The cost of this program will be up to $75,000 in HCP years 15.

attribute.attributeDefinition: The bark thickness ratio for a given species.

A factor used in Behre’s hyperbola, which describes tree form. Enter one of the following species codes to use an Ao factor base upon age (DF, LP, WH, RA, PP, SS, SF, RC or NF). For example, red alder and cottonwood have a similar tree bole form, so for both species in this column, RA may be entered (the Ao for red alder).
The diameter outside the bark measured at Form Point (generally 16 feet) divided by the diameter outside bark measured at D4H .
A one character wide alphabetic field, referring to the type of wood, used in reporting.
A one character alphabetic code used to classify species for reporting.
The yield equation that best mimics the volume yields for a given species.
The minimum allowed small-end diameter of a log for a particular tree species.
The overall minimum acceptable length of a log by species.
The ovarall maximum acceptable length of a log relative to scaling rules.
Excess length added on to the log that is not reported. It compensates for length that will be lost in processing at the mill.
The board foot rule to be employed. For example, depending on where the project is located, westside, eastside or doyle rules may be employed.
The cubic foot rule to be employed when calculating volumes.
The pounds of wood per either MBF or CCF
The volume unit used in the measurement of weight. Would enter an M for MBF or a C for CCF.
